{{Infobox person | name = Gladys West | birth_name = Gladys Mae Brown |birth_place = [[Dinwiddie County, Virginia]], [[United States]] | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1931}} | alma_mater = [[Virginia State College]] | known_for = [[GPS]] }}
'''Gladys Mae West''' (née '''Brown''') (born 1930<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" /> or 1931) is an American mathematician known for her contributions to the mathematics underpinning [[Global Positioning System]]s.
== Early life and education == West was born in [[Dinwiddie County, Virginia]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |url=http://www.fredericksburg.com/features/gladys-west-s-work-on-gps-would-impact-the-world/article_26e82f21-bb5a-5d76-9789-69a5039ad018.html |title=Gladys West's work on GPS 'would impact the world' |last=LANCE–STAR |first=CATHY DYSON THE FREE |work=Fredericksburg.com |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref> to a farming family in a community of [[sharecropper]]s.<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" /> After gaining a scholarship for achieving the first place in her high-school class,<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" /> she studied mathematics at [[Virginia State College]].<ref name=":0" /> After graduating she taught for around two years.<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" />
== Career == In 1956 West began to work at [[Naval Surface Warfare Center Dahlgren Division]], where she was the second black woman ever to be employed.<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" /><ref name=SPotomacPilot /> West began to collect data from [[satellites]], eventually leading to the development of [[Global Positioning System]].<ref >{{Cite news |url=https://www.stamfordadvocate.com/news/education/article/Gladys-West-s-work-on-GPS-would-impact-the-world-12545061.php |title=Gladys West's work on GPS 'would impact the world' |work=StamfordAdvocate |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref> Her supervisor Ralph Neiman recommended her as project manager for the [[Seasat]] radar altimetry project, the first satellite that could remotely sense oceans.<ref >{{Cite web |url=https://www.jpl.nasa.gov/missions/seasat |title=Seasat |website=www.jpl.nasa.gov |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref><ref >{{Cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraftDisplay.do?id=1978-064A |title=NASA - NSSDCA - Spacecraft - Details |website=nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref> In 1979, Neiman recommended West for commendation.<ref >{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantavoice.com/articles/celebrate-black-history-month-when-you-use-your-gps-remember-gladys-west/ |title=Celebrate Black History Month: When you use your GPS, remember Gladys West {{!}} The Atlanta Voice |date=2018-02-07 |work=The Atlanta Voice {{!}} Atlanta GA News |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref> West was a programmer in the Dahlgren Division for large-scale computers and a project manager for data-processing systems used in the analysis of satellite data.<ref >{{Cite web |url=http://dahlgrenmuseum.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=96:forum-to-recount-impact-of-the-war-years-on-dahlgren-and-region&catid=40:press&Itemid=78 |title=Forum to Recount Impact of the War Years on Dahlgren and Region |date=2015-06-11 |website=Dahlgren Museum |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref>
[[File:Data processing for GeoSat.png|thumb|Data processing report for GeoSat by Gladys West]] In 1986, West published "Data Processing System Specifications for the Geosat Satellite Radar Altimeter", a 60-page illustrated guide. The [[Naval Surface Weapons Center]] (NSWC) guide was published to explain how to increase the accuracy of the estimation of "[[geoid height]]s and [[vertical deflection]]", topics of [[satellite geodesy]].<ref name=Dyson2018/> This was achieved by processing the data created from the [[radio altimeter]] on the [[Geosat|Geosat satellite]] which went into orbit on 12 March 1984.<ref >{{Cite web |url=http://www.dtic.mil/get-tr-doc/pdf?Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf&AD=ADA181113 |title=Data Processing System Specifications for the Geosat Satellite Radar Altimeter |year=1986 |publisher=Naval Surface Weapons Center |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref> She worked at Dahlgren for 42 years,<ref name=":1">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/gladys-wests-work-on-gps-would-impact-the-world/2018/02/01/f5bf9466-07c2-11e8-aa61-f3391373867e_story.html |title=Gladys West's work on GPS 'would impact the world' |last=Dyson {{!}} AP|first=Cathy |date=2018-02-01 |work=[[Washington Post]] |access-date=2018-02-09 |language=en-US |issn=0190-8286 }}</ref> retiring in 1998.<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" /> Her contributions to [[GPS]] were only uncovered when a member of West's sorority, [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]], read a short biography West had submitted for an alumni function.<ref name=Dyson2018 >{{Cite news |url=http://www.fredericksburg.com/features/gladys-west-s-work-on-gps-would-impact-the-world/article_26e82f21-bb5a-5d76-9789-69a5039ad018.html |title=Gladys West's work on GPS 'would impact the world' |work=[[The Free Lance–Star]] |author=Cathy Dyson |date=2018-01-19 |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref> For this work, West was listed by the BBC as part of their 2018 [[100 Women (BBC)|100 Women]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-46225037|title=BBC 100 Women 2018: Who is on the list?|date=2018-11-19|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-21|language=en-GB}}</ref>
==Personal life== She met her husband Ira West at the naval base and they married in 1957.<ref name="BBC, 100 Women" /><ref name=SPotomacPilot>{{Cite news |url=https://issuu.com/dcmilitary/docs/sppt_061915 |title=Sppt 061915 |work=South Potomac Pilot |access-date=2018-02-09}}</ref> {{As of|February 2018}}, West lives in [[King George County, Virginia]],<ref name=":1" /> and is completing a PhD via a distance-learning program with [[Virginia Tech]].<ref >{{Cite news |url=https://www.becauseofthemwecan.com/blogs/stories/meet-gladys-west-one-of-the-hidden-figures-behind-the-creation-of-the-gps-system |title=Meet Gladys West: One Of The 'Hidden Figures' Behind The Creation Of The GPS System |work=BECAUSE OF THEM, WE CAN |access-date=2018-02-09 }}</ref>
