The '''Groceries Code Adjudicator''' (or ''Supermarket Ombudsman'') <ref>BBC News, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21117701 Christine Tacon named as supermarket ombudsman]</ref> is an independent statutory office responsible for enforcing the Groceries Supply Code of Practice and to regulate the relationship between [[supermarket]]s and their direct suppliers within the [[United Kingdom]]. The post was created by the [[Groceries Code Adjudicator Act 2013]] and is an independent office within the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]].
The [https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/groceries-supply-code-of-practice Groceries Supply Code of Practice] applies to ten retailers with an annual turnover of £1bn+, namely [[Tesco]] [[Co-op]], [[Sainsbury’s]], [[Marks and Spencer]], [[Asda]], [[Lidl]], [[Morrisons]], [[Aldi]], [[Waitrose]] and [[Iceland (supermarket)|Iceland]].
The UK [[Competition Commission]] ({{As of|2014|4|1|lc=y}} the [[Competition and Markets Authority]]) undertook an investigation of grocery retail in 2009, and recommended that government establish an ombudsman for the sector.<ref name="The Daily Telegraph - 4 August 2009 - Competition Commission calls for retail ombudsman">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/5973553/Competition-Commission-calls-for-retail-ombudsman.html|title=Competition Commission calls for retail ombudsman|date=4 August 2009|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]]|accessdate=20 April 2014}}</ref>
[[Trade magazine]] and website ''Retail Week'' reported that in response to calls for submissions to the Competition Commission investigation, major UK retailer [[Aldi]] supported the establishment of a retail ombudsman, while [[Tesco]], [[Sainsbury's]], and a number of other major retailers did not support its establishment.<ref name="Retail Week - 5 June 2009 - Waitrose gives last-minute show of support for retail ombudsman">{{cite news|url=http://www.retail-week.com/sectors/food/waitrose-gives-last-minute-show-of-support-for-retail-ombudsman/5003290.article|title=Waitrose gives last-minute show of support for retail ombudsman|last=Faithfull|first=Mark|date=5 June 2009|work=[[Retail Week]]|publisher=[[Emap International Limited]]|accessdate=20 April 2014}}</ref>
In January 2013 [[Christine Tacon]] was appointed to the role for a four-year period.<ref>UK Government, [https://www.gov.uk/government/people/christine-tacon Christine Tacon CBE]</ref> Her first investigation was into the [[supply chain]] activities of [[Tesco plc]].<ref>BBC News, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-35408064 Tesco knowingly delayed payments to suppliers], 26 January 2016, accessed 22 October 2017</ref>
The adjudicator publishes interpretative guidance on the Code of Practice, best practice statements and details of retailers' voluntary commitments <ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/510114/GCA_policy__Interpretive_guidance__best_practice_and_voluntary_agreements_March_2016.pdf GCA policy: Interpretative guidance, best practice statements and retailer voluntary commitments], March 2016</ref> and arbitrates in disputes between retailers and suppliers.
