'''Kidan habesha''' (alt. '''ije tebab''') is a clothing style from [[Eritrea]].<ref name="Dresser2011">{{cite book|author=Norine Dresser|title=Multicultural Manners: Essential Rules of Etiquette for the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Brrmm0cDHz0C&pg=PA206|date=7 January 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-04028-7|pages=206–}}</ref> It comprises a white [[shirt]] and [[pants]]. Then a thin, [[gauze]]-like, fabric is wrapped around the shoulders and chest. Sometimes, men take the extra material and wrap it around their waist making a [[skirt]] on top of their pants, then wrap it around their shoulders. This kind of clothing is worn with intricately designed stick and white [[shoe]]s. It is mostly worn at weddings and cultural events.

[[Category:Eritrean clothing]]

